  "prompt": "Can you be a pilot if you wear glasses?",
  "response": "Yes, you can be a pilot if you wear glasses. Many pilots wear corrective lenses, such as glasses or contact lenses, to meet the necessary vision requirements. The key factor is that your vision, when corrected, must meet the standards set by the aviation authority in the country where you are obtaining your pilot's license. For example, in the United States, the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) requires private pilots to have at least 20/40 vision with or without correction and commercial pilots to have 20/20 vision with or without correction. Similar standards apply in other countries, but it's essential to check the specific requirements of the aviation authority you are dealing with.\n\nAdditionally, pilots are required to carry a spare pair of corrective lenses when flying, and regular medical examinations are mandatory to ensure their vision remains adequate for flying safely.",
